                            <item><note xml:lang="en" xml:id="harkavy-cards" anchored="true">
<p part="N">Avraham E. Harkavy (1835-1919) was appointed to the department of Jewish literature and  oriental manuscripts at the Imperial Public Library of St. Petersburg in 1868. In 1876, he was  made head of the Department of Hebrew Books (Hebrew Department), and in 1877 appointed as  ordinary librarian, a position which he held for the rest of his life. He was the first  curator of the Firkovich collections. His unpublished cataloging of these collections consists  of slips of paper (“Harkavy-Cards”) placed together with each manuscript that record his  identification and/or brief description of the respective manuscript. These slips were the  foundation for his handwritten four-volume inventory of the Yevr.-Arab. section of the Second  Firkovich Collection.</p>
</note> 
                                <persName instant="false" full="yes">Avraham Harkavy</persName> <quote xml:lang="ru"><p part="N">p. 3<lb/> N. 216 (414)<lb/> Изъ коммент. на Притчи Соломона<lb/> Йефета<lb/> I<lb/> 21 л.<lb/> </p></quote> <bibl default="false" status="draft"> <title>Avraham E. Harkavy. Harkavy Cards (ru.)</title>  <ptr target="https://jalit.org/bibl/BTVBSSXB"/> </bibl> </item>
                            <item><note xml:lang="en" xml:id="harkavy-cards" anchored="true">
<p part="N">Avraham E. Harkavy (1835-1919) was appointed to the department of Jewish literature and  oriental manuscripts at the Imperial Public Library of St. Petersburg in 1868. In 1876, he was  made head of the Department of Hebrew Books (Hebrew Department), and in 1877 appointed as  ordinary librarian, a position which he held for the rest of his life. He was the first  curator of the Firkovich collections. His unpublished cataloging of these collections consists  of slips of paper (“Harkavy-Cards”) placed together with each manuscript that record his  identification and/or brief description of the respective manuscript. These slips were the  foundation for his handwritten four-volume inventory of the Yevr.-Arab. section of the Second  Firkovich Collection.</p>
</note> 
                                <persName instant="false" full="yes">Avraham Harkavy</persName> <quote xml:lang="en"><p part="N">p. 3<lb/> N. 216 (414)<lb/> From a commentary on Proverbs<lb/> By Yefet[?]<lb/> I<lb/> 21 folios<lb/> corresponds to p. 2<lb/> </p></quote> <bibl default="false" status="draft"> <title>Avraham E. Harkavy. Harkavy Cards (en.)</title>  <ptr target="https://jalit.org/bibl/BTVBSSXB"/> </bibl> </item>
                            <item> <note xml:lang="en" anchored="true">
    <p part="N">The “Harkavy-Cards” were the foundation for his handwritten four-volume inventory of the  Yevr.-Arab. section of the Second Firkovich Collection. This inventory is today held at the  Vernadsky Library of the Ukrainian Academy of Sciences in Kiev, and also served as basis of  the library’s card catalog prepared over the years by Harkavy, F. Kokovtzov, R. Ravrebe, A.  Vasilev and V. Lebedev.</p>
</note>
                                <persName instant="false" full="yes">Avraham Harkavy</persName> <quote xml:lang="he"> / מפי׳ משלי (ליפת, לפי׳ דברי אגור בן יקה (ל׳ א׳; ועל הגליון רשום מ״ז) כטוב אלמגמוע בן אלמתקאי וכו׳ אחרי תרגום הפסוק אל תוסף וכו׳ יתחיל הפי׳ כזה:קולהדבריאגורינתהיאלידברילמואלואגורהושלמהולה ה̇ אסמאוהישלמהידידיהאגור:למואל:קוהלת:וכלואחדמןהדהאלה̇ אסמאלהמעני:פסמאהשלמהלמעניושלוםושקטאתןעליש̇ בימ̇: וסמאה ידידיה לאן אללה חבה כק̇ ויי̇ אהבו וכו׳ וכו׳ / Bundle number: </quote> <bibl default="false" status="draft">
